Description: THE INLAND EMPIRE TREE IMPROVEMENT COOPERATIVE (IETIC) WAS ESTABLISHED IN 1967 TO APPLY CLASSICAL TECHNIQUES TO IMPROVE THE QUALITY OF IMPORTANT NATIVE TREE SPECIES FOR REFORESTATION AND ECOSYSTEM RESTORATION. THE BUREAU OF LAND MANAGEMENT (BLM) HAS BEEN A MEMBER OF IETIC SINCE ITS INCEPTION.THE IETIC OPERATING AREA INCLUDES THE PRODUCTIVE FOREST REGIONS OF EASTERN WASHINGTON, NORTHERN IDAHO, AND WESTERN MONTANA. IN THIS AREA, BLM MANAGES APPROXIMATELY 106,000 ACRES OF FOREST LAND. IN COMPLIANCE WITH THE BLM MISSION, THESE LANDS ARE MANAGED TO SUSTAIN HEALTH, DIVERSITY, AND PRODUCTIVITY FOR THE USE AND ENJOYMENT OF PRESENT AND FUTURE GENERATIONS.THE MISSION OF IETIC IS TO: TO IDENTIFY IMPROVED SEED AND TREES FOR REFORESTATION AND ECOSYSTEM RESTORATION. TO DEVELOP AND DEMONSTRATE METHODS FOR PRODUCING GENETICALLY IMPROVED FOREST TREES, SEED AND OTHER PLANT MATERIALS. TO CONSERVE, IMPROVE, AND UTILIZE THE FOREST TREE GENETIC RESOURCE OF THE NORTHERN ROCKY MOUNTAINS.

THE PURPOSE OF THIS AWARD IS TO STRENGTHEN THE WORKING RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN THE BUREAU OF LAND MANAGEMENT  BLM  AND THE NATIONAL FOREST FOUNDATION  NFF  TO ADVANCE CROSS BOUNDARY VEGETATION AND FUELS MANAGEMENT PROJECTS IN COLORADO  IT WOULD BE MUTUALLY BENEFICIAL TO ESTABLISH A FRAMEWORK FOR OUR ORGANIZATIONS TO COLLABORATE ON PROJECTS TO ACCOMPLISH MUTUAL GOALS  THE BLM MISSION IS TO SUSTAIN THE HEALTH, DIVERSITY, AND PRODUCTIVITY OF PUBLIC LANDS FOR THE USE AND ENJOYMENT OF PRESENT AND FUTURE GENERATIONS  THE MISSION OF THE NFF IS TO ENGAGE AMERICANS IN COMMUNITY BASED AND NATIONAL PROGRAMS THAT PROMOTE THE HEALTH AND PUBLIC ENJOYMENT OF THE 193 MILLION ACRE NATIONAL FOREST AND GRASSLANDS SYSTEM AND TO ADMINISTER PRIVATE GIFTS OF FUNDS FOR THE BENEFIT OF NATIONAL FORESTS AND GRASSLANDS  IN MANY INSTANCES IN COLORADO, THE BLM AND NFF ARE SEEING OPPORTUNITIES TO WORK IN SHARED STEWARDSHIP ACROSS JURISDICTIONAL BOUNDARIES  IN AREAS WHERE THE NFF IS ALREADY WORKING WITH THE U S  FOREST SERVICE TO TREAT NATIONAL FOREST SYSTEM AND PRIVATE LAND, THE NFF AND BLM COULD GAIN EFFICIENCIES BY ALSO TREATING BLM LANDS

PROJECT SUPPORTS TNC S WESTERN MONTANA SHARED FORESTER  WMSF , WESTERN MONTANA FORESTRY AND STEWARDSHIP ASSISTANT  WMFSA  AND POTENTIALLY OTHER TNC STEWARDSHIP STAFF  THESE ARE POSITIONS THAT  TAKE ON THE GROUND ACTION TO CONFRONT THE CHALLENGES FACING MONTANA S FORESTS  ORIGINALLY CREATED IN 2017 WITH SUPPORT FROM THE BLM, MONTANA FISH WILDLIFE AND PARKS  MT FWP , AND THE BLACKFOOT CHALLENGE, THE WMSF FOCUSES ON CRITICAL FOREST RESTORATION AND CLIMATE CHANGE ADAPTION OPPORTUNITIES IN WESTERN MONTANA  THE WMSF HAS AND WILL CONTINUE TO FOCUS ON ECOLOGICALLY BASED TIMBER HARVEST, NON COMMERCIAL THINNING AND PRESCRIBED FIRE  THE WMFSA WILL BE AN INTERN OR SEASONAL POSITION FORM A PARTNERING ORGANIZATION SUCH AS MONTANA CONSERVATION CORPS, SALISH KOOTENAI COLLEGE, UNIVERSITY OF MONTANA OR SIMILAR ACADEMIC OR NGO ORGANIZATION  THE WMFSA MAY ALSO BE A TNC SEASONAL EMPLOYEE  THE WMFSA WILL ASSIST THE WMSF AND OTHER TNC STAFF TO COMPLETE THIS WORK AND OTHER ASSOCIATED LAND STEWARDSHIP AND RECREATION MANAGEMENT  THIS WORK DIRECTLY IMPROVES THE ECOLOGICAL CONDITION AND RESILIENCY OF MONTANA FORESTS  THESE POSITIONS WILL TAKE AN  ALL LANDS  APPROACH, FOCUSING ON ACTIVE FOREST RESTORATION, FUELS REDUCTION IN THE WILDLAND URBAN INTERFACE  WUI  AND CROSS BOUNDARY MANAGEMENT, TO MAKE MONTANA S FORESTS RESILIENT IN THE FACE OF CLIMATE CHANGE  THE WORK COMPLETED BY THE WMSF AND WMFSA WILL FOCUS ON THE FORMER INDUSTRIAL TIMBERLANDS THAT TNC CURRENTLY MANAGES  MANY OF THESE LANDS WILL LIKELY HEAD TOWARDS FEDERAL  BLM OR USFS  OR STATE OWNERSHIP OVER THE NEXT DECADE AS PART OF TNC S DECADES LONG EFFORTS TO MEND THE LEGACY OF CHECKERBOARD  THIS WORK, MUCH OF WHICH WILL BE DIRECTED TOWARD LIKELY FUTURE BLM LAND ACQUISITIONS, WILL IMPROVE THE CONDITIONS OF THESE LANDS BEFORE THEY ARE ACQUIRED  CONTINUED BLM SUPPORT WILL BUILD AND LEVERAGE INTERAGENCY PARTNERSHIPS AS WELL AS OTHER FEDERAL, STATE, AND PRIVATE FUNDING TO ACCOMPLISH LANDSCAPE SCAPE FOREST RESTORATION EFFORTS ACROSS OWNERSHIPS BY WORKING WITH UNIVERSITIES AND AGENCY SCIENTISTS, THE WMSF AND WMFSA HELP TO DEVELOP RESEARCH AND CONNECT MANAGERS AND RESEARCHERS IN AN ADAPTIVE MANAGEMENT FRAMEWORK TO FIND MANAGEMENT SOLUTIONS THAT ADDRESS CHALLENGES IN WESTERN MONTANA S FORESTED ECOSYSTEMS  THIS BUILDS RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN AGENCIES, COMMUNITY ORGANIZATIONS AND LOCAL COMMUNITIES AROUND RESTORATION TO IMPROVE THE CONDITION OF THE FORESTS AND BUILD SUPPORT FOR LONG TERM OWNERSHIP AND MANAGEMENT OF THESE LANDS  THE LONG TERM OBJECTIVES OF THE WMSF AND WMFSA ARE TO BUILD TRUST AMONG A DIVERSE GROUP OF STAKEHOLDERS AND SERVE AS A CATALYST FOR MORE FOREST RESTORATION ACROSS ALL OWNERSHIPS, MAKING MONTANA S FORESTS RESILIENT IN THE FACE OF DISTURBANCE AND CLIMATE CHANGE TO SUSTAIN WILDLIFE, OUR COMMUNITIES AND OUR WAY OF LIFE  THE WORK WILL PRINCIPALLY OCCUR ON THE FOLLOWING TNC LANDS   1  THE MONTANA CHECKERBOARD PROJECT,  2  BALDY MTN FOREST RESERVE,  3  OTHER W MT TNC LANDS TARGETS RESTORATION BASED COMMERCIAL HARVEST   250 1,000 ACRES YEARPRECOMMERCIAL THINNING MASTICATION   250 750 ACRES YEAR PRESCRIBED FIRE  1 4 BURNS PER YEAR, TOTALING  50 400  ACRES YEARDEVELOP AND IMPLEMENT LANDSCAPE LEVEL RESTORATION TREATMENTS THAT INCREASE THE RESILIENCE OF THE LANDSCAPETO FIRE, INSECTS, AND DISEASE IMPROVE FOREST INVENTORIES COORDINATE WITH PARTNERS TO CREATE OUTREACH PRESS ABOUT FOREST RESTORATION WORK STRENGTHEN PARTNERSHIPS WITH LOCAL ORGANIZATIONS AND UNIVERSITY OF MONTANA TO CREATE APPLIED SCIENCE INFOREST RESTORATION ON TNC LANDS

UNDERSTANDING THE LANDSLIDE HAZARD WHICH THREATENS THE STUDY AREA  BLM COOS BAY DISTRICT   THE BLM HAS PRIORITIZED THE AREAS OF MAPPING BY WATERSHED IN THE DISTRICT  TO CONTINUE MAPPING THE LANDSLIDE INVENTORY BY USING RECENTLY ACQUIRED LIDAR DATA IN THE STUDY AREA

THIS AERIAL MULCHING PROJECT WILL TREAT 1,811 ACRES OF BLM LANDS WITHIN THE EAST TROUBLESOME FIREBURN AREA BY STABILIZING BURNED HILLSLOPES AND REDUCING PEAK FLOW RUNOFF INTO ADJACENTWATERBODIES. HELICOPTER APPLICATION OF WOOD MULCH WILL SERVE TO PREVENT EROSION, REDUCE RUNOFF,AND CONTRIBUTE TOWARDS REVEGETATION.WOOD MULCH HAS BEEN SHOWN TO REDUCE PEAK FLOWS AND INCREASE SOIL MOISTURE WHICH SPEEDSREVEGETATION. BY REDUCING OVERLAND FLOW FROM BARE SOILS, THE TOTAL SEDIMENT LOAD AND PEAK FLOWSTO UNSTABLE STREAM REACHES IS ALSO REDUCED. UNSTABLE STREAM REACHES ARE PARTICULARLY VULNERABLETO FURTHER EROSION. LARGE PEAK FLOWS AND SEDIMENTS COMING FROM THE HILLSLOPE CAN AMPLIFY INSTREAMEROSION AND LEAD TO MASSIVE BANK FAILURES ULTIMATELY CONTRIBUTING TO DEBRIS FLOWS. THIS IS ACONCERN NOT ONLY FOR NATURAL RESOURCES BUT ALSO FOR PROPERTY AND LIVES.THE AREAS TREATED UNDER FUNDING FROM BLM WILL PROVIDE

THIS PROJECT WILL DEVELOP AND/OR IMPROVE FUEL BREAKS TO PROTECT EXISTING INFRASTRUCTURE, REDUCE FUEL LOADING AROUND INFRASTRUCTURE AND ALONG ROADS, KEEP BLM ACCESS ROADS OPEN FOR FAST FIRE RESPONSE TO MINIMIZE FIRE SPREAD TO NEIGHBORING LANDS AND MAINTAIN WATER SOURCES TO PROVIDE WATER FOR FIRE SUPPRESSION RESOURCES. THESE ACTIVITIES WILL IMPROVE OVERALL COMMUNITY PREPAREDNESS FOR IMPENDING WILDFIRES FOR ALL STAKE HOLDERS.
